In addition to the surface Pd atom, we find that the electric field induces magnetism also on the sub-surface Pd atom. The sub-surface palladium atom has a much lower DOS at the Fermi level than the surface atom, never meeting the Stoner criterion (
\(I\rho_{F}\approx 0.7\)
). However, there is a significant magnetic moment induced on this atom above the critical electric field. We also observe that the DOS at the Fermi level on the sub-surface monolayer changes with the electric field, even though the screening charges are almost entirely localized on the surface monolayer. The change in the electronic DOS induced by the screening charge on the surface Pd monolayer is partly transferred to the subsurface Pd monolayer due to hybridization between the neighboring Pd atoms. This effect results in induced magnetization on the sub-surface Pd monolayer, similar to previous calculations on different systems where a magnetic Co atom was predicted to induce a magnetic moment on an adjacent Ti atom.

