. However, different Fermi-level conditions will favor either positively or negatively charged defects.

This suggested mechanism provides an explanation for the observed effect of Ti or other transition metals. Ti acts as an electrically active dopant that shifts the Fermi level, leading to a lowering of the formation energy of hydrogen-related defects. An upward shift in the Fermi level, such as that introduced by Ti, makes it energetically more favorable for the vacancy to be in the negative charge state rather than the positive charge state. For instance, if the Fermi level shifts upward by 0.44 eV, the formation energy of the negatively charged vacancy (
$V_{m H}^{-}
) decreases by 0.44 eV, increasing its concentration by six orders of magnitude at 100°C. This energy gain explains the lowering in activation energy for decomposition and desorption in the presence of an electrically active impurity. Furthermore, the repulsion between components of the 
$H_{i}^{-}-V_{m H}^{-}
 pair eliminates any additional energy cost for their separation into isolated defects.

